╭─ Assistant [MainThread@3317356] ─────────────────────────────╮
│ The bug is an incorrect transformation of a `select` pattern │
│ into `fabs`. The transformation is `select(x <= 0, -x, x) -> │
│ fabs(x)`. This is incorrect for NaN inputs when no fast-math │
│ flags are present. Specifically, for a negative signaling    │
│ NaN, `fcmp ole` returns false, so the `select` returns the   │
│ original negative sNaN. However, `fabs` would clear the sign │
│ bit, returning a positive sNaN. This discrepancy makes the   │
│ transformation unsafe without the `nnan` (no NaNs) fast-math │
│ flag.                                                        │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to ensure this transformation is only performed   │
│ when it's safe. The `fcmp` instruction involved in the       │
│ condition must have the `nnan` flag. The original code was   │
│ missing this check for the pattern involving `fsub`.         │
│                                                              │
│ I will add a check for `hasNoNaNs()` on the `fcmp`           │
│ instruction (`CondVal`) before allowing the transformation   │
│ to `fabs`. This ensures the optimization is only applied     │
│ when the NaN semantics do not cause a mismatch.              │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp  │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp  │
│ @@ -2793,6 +2793,13 @@                                       │
│      // fold (X <= +/-0.0) ? (0.0 - X) : X to fabs(X), when  │
│ 'Swap' is false                                              │
│      // fold (X >  +/-0.0) ? X : (0.0 - X) to fabs(X), when  │
│ 'Swap' is true                                               │
│      if (match(TrueVal, m_FSub(m_PosZeroFP(),                │
│ m_Specific(X)))) {                                           │
│ +      // This transform is only safe with the nnan flag.    │
│ +      // fcmp ole <snan>, 0 -> false                        │
│ +      // select false, <ignored>, <snan> -> <snan>          │
│ +      // fabs(<snan>) -> <qnan> with sign bit cleared.      │
│ +      if (!cast<FPMathOperator>(CondVal)->hasNoNaNs())      │
│ +        continue;                                           │
│ +                                                            │
│        if (!Swap && (Pred == FCmpInst::FCMP_OLE || Pred ==   │
│ FCmpInst::FCMP_ULE)) {                                       │
│          Value *Fabs =                                       │
│ IC.Builder.CreateUnaryIntrinsic(Intrinsic::fabs, X, &SI);    │
│          return IC.replaceInstUsesWith(SI, Fabs);            │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
